<https://colonial-heritage.triply.cc/nmvw/id/object/RV-335-30> <https://colonialcollections.nl/schema#description> "Kwakwaka’wakh Nuhlamahl mask; ca. 1820-1850\r\nWood, paint; h. 29,3 cm., w. 22,5 cm.;\r\nRMV 335-30; purchased from dealer Charles Jamrach, London 1883\r\n\r\nThe performance of the Nuhlamahl is one of the oldest ceremonial traditions of the Kwakwaka'wakw, who live on the north end of Vancouver Island and the adjacent British Columbia mainland. By way of intermarriage and warfare in the nineteenth century, the Nuhlamahl performance spread out to the neighboring Nuxalk people to the north along the BC coast and to the Nuu-chah-nulth bands on the northwest corner of Vancouver Island. The general characteristics of the Nuhlamahl image include a long or large nose, drooping eyebrows, an encircling ring of twisted cedar bark, and often the depiction of mucous flowing from the nostrils. The Nuhlamahl is known in English as the Foolish or Reckless Dancer, and the performance dramatizes the souls of people who have been consumed by a wild, chaotic spirit power that causes unsocial behavior and a constantly running nose. The masked dancers also function as enforcers of ritual conventions during the Winter Ceremonial. Despite being hugely sensitive of their oversized and problematic noses, they were known to punish mistakes and errors of tradition with wild, frantic behaviors.\r\n\r\n\tA wide range of regional and individual carver’s styles appear in Nuhlamahl masks from the historic period. The earliest documented examples of these masks originated on the northwest tip of Vancouver Island, in an area known as Quatsino Sound, named after a prominent village located on its shore. A unique sub-style of Nuhlamahl masks was developed there, the earliest of which was collected in 1842. The inspiration for these unusual masks seems to have been drawn from an unexpected source.\r\n\r\n\tEuro-American ships of the fur trade were common visitors to certain Kwakwaka'wakw territories, particularly Quatsino Sound, due to the numerous populations of sea otter along the outer coast. One of the most common decorative elements on these early square-rigged ships was the head of a lion, and an important universal element of these vessels was known as the cat-head timber. This stout beam extended out from the bow quarters of the hull and supported strong pulleys that were employed in securing the heavy stocked anchors to the side of the ship, which prevented damage to the hull in a seaway. The process was known as ‘catting the anchor’, and the cathead timber was often appropriately adorned with a lion’s-head carving. These lions had large snouts, drooping eyebrows, a swirling mane that looked similar to cedar bark, and representations of whiskers that reminded Kwakwaka'wakw carvers of mucous flowing from the nose. These lion images appear to have given rise to what has been called the leonine style of Nuhlamahl carvings, of which the subject mask is a somewhat simplified example.\r\n\r\n\tA number of carvers from the Quatsino region appear to have created examples of the leonine Nuhlamahl, as evidenced by a certain range of personal styles in which they can be found. Sufficient similarities exist, however, to suggest that most if not all of the leonine masks originated in this once-remote location. The classic leonine masks are of course very catlike, while this one is much more humanoid in appearance. Its maker, whose style can be seen in some masks of the classic leonine type, appears to have refined down some of the more overtly lion-like characteristics in favor of a more human form. Nonetheless it displays the drooping brows, an elongated nose, an unusual grin, and the face is encircled with spiral forms in alternating colors that represent the twisted cedar bark rope associated with the Nuhlamahl. The round face, large eyes of a particular form, the eyesocket shape, and the character of the surrounding swirls connect this mask to the ones of more leonine form made by this carver.\r\n\r\n\tContemporary Kwakwaka'wakw artist Beau Dick has suggested that the adaptation of a Euro-American image to represent the Nuhlamahl may not have been solely due to visual similarity. The selection of a Euro-American symbol to portray an obnoxious, crazy, rule-enforcing character may well have had its own secret significance that added a touch of ironic humor to the performance.\r\n\r\nSteven C. Brown; 2015\r\n\r\nNoelmaal-masker. Noelmaal wordt vaak voorgesteld als een clown, maar in wezen speelt hij een belangrijke rol. Noelmaal ontvangt zijn geestelijke kracht van \"atlasamk\", bovennatuurlijke wezens die in een drijvend dorp op een meer op een eiland leven. De mythe verhaalt over een beverjager die daar terecht kwam, naar huis terugkeerde en ziek werd. Hij kreeg een snotneus die niet wilde ophouden en zijn gedrag werd steeds afstotelijker doordat hij zijn snot at of het over zijn lichaam uitsmeerde. Ook deed hij zijn behoefte binnenshuis. Dit werd beschouwd als spirituele bezetenheid en het duurde lang voordat zijn familie en de sjamanen zijn geestelijke gezondheid weer hadden hersteld.\r\n\r\nDatzelfde asociale gedrag vertoont de Noelmaal tijdens feesten en ceremonies en toont darmee de toeschouwers welk gedrag onoirbaar is. Zijn optreden is lachwekkend en afschrikkend en hij wordt ook Gekke Danser genoemd. Vanwege de angst die hij inboezemt speelt hij ook de rol van toezichthouder op respectvol gedrag tijdens ceremonies. Ook corrigeert hij dansers die zich niet aan de voorgeschreven regels houden. De vergelijking met de rol van de hofnar is geen toevallige. Noelmaal kondigt ook de komst van de kannibalen-geesten aan die hij assisteert.\r\n\r\nNoelmaal wordt vaak maar niet altijd herkend aan zijn grote neus. Oudere maskers tonen een meer normale neus dan latere maskers. Zijn naam betekent \"Gek Gezicht\". De krans om zijn gezicht en hoofd is een gevlochten krans van ongeverfde en geverfde cederbast, een soort hoofdring die tijdens speciale ceremonies wordt gedragen. Mogelijk werden sommige maskers ook beïnvloed door het snijwerk dat Indiaanse houtsnijders op Europese en Amerikaanse zeilschepen zagen, met name de leeuwenkoppen met hun manen." .
